entry.title: [omnibox] Fix starter pack `allowed_to_be_default`
entry.content:
tldr:



When `kOmniboxKeywordModeRefresh` is disabled, we want starter packs to

be default, but that wasn't always the case (see 1 and 2 below).



When `kOmniboxKeywordModeRefresh` is enabled, we want starter packs to

never be default, but that too wasn't always the case (see 3 below).



1) Starter pack suggestions were supposed to be scored 1350. But they

were being conditionally overwritten to 1250 in

`UpdateRelevanceScores()` which was only supposed to score the

non-starter-pack built in suggestions. This CL changes

`UpdateRelevanceScores()` to be called before

`DoStarterPackAutocompletion()` to ensure starter pack scores aren't

overwritten.



2) 1350 was chosen to outscore search suggestions. But It doesn't

outscore HUP suggestions. And since HUP apparently ignores the '@' in

the input, inputs like '@b' would default 'bing.com' scored 1413;

likewise, '@t' would default 'twitter.com'. This CL increases the

starter pack scores to 1450, high enough to outscore HUP.



3) When `kOmniboxKeywordModeRefresh` was enabled, starter pack

suggestions should not be allowed be default. That would allow users

to type '@tquery' to do tab search instead of accidentally

moving out of tab scope. It would also allow users to do '@b' to

enter bookmark scope instead of having to do '@b'. I.e.

auto-entering keyword mode when it wasn't intended would require the

user to repeatedly press backspace. Although

`kOmniboxKeywordModeRefresh` set `allowed_to_be_default` to false

when constructing the starter pack suggestions, it was overwritten in

`UpdateRelevanceScores()` causing the backspace bugs and a few other

bugs regarding up/down/tab/shift-tab selection changes. This CL cals

`UpdateRelevanceScores()` before `DoStarterPackAutocompletion()` so

starterpack suggestions' `allowed_to_be_default` isn't overwritten.

entry.title: [A11y] Do not allow asymmetrical parent-child relations in tree
entry.content:
Design doc:

https://docs.google.com/document/d/1PnjhlWqTtivmsUVTF0kqMAUIsO9a_eTp32pRY4KJh_U/edit#heading=h.wlgzk7gh4m76



Fix failures brought to light by the Eager AX Tree Updates project and related checks, so that serialization operates on a truly frozen, complete AX Tree, and does not lead to changes to the underlying data at unsafe times. After landing this CL and any follow-ups, the goal is to have a vastly more stable, predictable Blink accessibility engine.



The current implementation can lead to processing the tree when there

are "holes" in the data structure, such as missing parents or children,

which can lead to crashes, checks and unpredictability.



1. Avoid holes in the first place: do not call AXObject::ClearChildren() immediately when calling AXObject::SetNeedsToUpdateChildren(), so that missing parent and missing child holes are not created for unchanged siblings. These holes tended to sit around and cause problems when downstream operations did not expect them. Only call ClearChildren() right before rebuilding the children, in UpdateChildrenIfNecessary().

2. More complete repairs: Instead of only repairing missing parents, when a parentless ensure a complete subtree structure around the child, starting with the included parent. The new method to accomplish this is called AXObjectCacheImpl::RepairIncludedParentsChildren(). It makes sure that every parent up to the included parent has a complete set of children.

3. More timely repairs: instead of waiting for a hole to be discovered while tree walking, eagerly ensure that objects up to their included parent have repairs, whenever an object is being retrieved for deferred event processing, or when an object is being created in the middle of a tree. If the necessary parents do not exist, and thus the AXObject itself is not viable, make sure any stale AXObjects in that subtree are eagerly removed, because they are also not viable.

4. More complete tree structure checks in AXObjectCacheImpl::CheckTreeIsUpdated(), which ensure symmetrical included parent-child relationships are complete. This helps guarantee that no lazy computations try to alter the tree while it’s being serialized (in a frozen state). The new checks do not pass without the other code changes, which are in service of the new checks.



Future work: attempt to avoid any tree repairs and guarantee completeness in more places, providing even more predictability, for example, by handling CSS display changes similarly to role changes.

entry.title: Make scroll snap more aware of browser controls.
entry.content:
Snap positions were frequently off by the height of browser controls,

and snap animations interacted poorly with viewport resizing, generally

leading to a janky experience for snap on the root scroller.



Five changes are made to improve the situation:



(1) Blink calculates the snapport using LayoutBox::OverflowClipRect

instead of PhysicalPaddingBoxRect. This measures the layout

viewport rather than the initial containing block, and corresponds

better to what the user sees.



(2) Update the SnapContainerData when the WebView is resized, even if

there is no layout change. But, defer snapping in response to a

container data change until the scroll gesture is finished, or else

the instant snap on main may fight with the cc snap animation.



(3) Use browser controls geometry to monkey-patch the snapport when cc

looks for snap positions. If a fling is also showing or hiding the

browser controls, we try to anticipate the true viewport size, even

though the WebView hasn't been resized yet.



(4) When a snap fling animation finishes, snap again (also animated), in

case the snap container data changed since the animation began.

This (along with #2) ensures we never stay in an invalid position.



(5) Snap when animating browser controls. This is an edge case where

the compositor can scroll the viewport after the user gesture is

finished, so we cannot rely solely on InputHandler::SnapAtScrollEnd.

entry.title: [Privacy Sandbox] Fix race conditions in attestations parsing.
entry.content:
The attestations_parse_progress_, file_version_, and attestations_map_

are accessed by both UI thread and thread pool. This CL changes to use

the `PostTaskAndReplyWithResult` pattern to to remove undefined

behavior due to data races.



This should also fix the other issue that the parsing progress is

marked as finished before the final assignment of the attestations map

in UI thread. When an attestations query takes place at this moment,

the metrics will record the file is corrupted because it sees the

progress is finished but the attestations map is not there.



Note chrome component updater's `ComponentReady` always runs on the UI

thread.

entry.title: [setup] Stop CloseHandle crash in child proc
entry.content:
When updating an enterprise install of Chrome (i.e., one that originates

from the MSI installer), setup.exe spins off a child process to update

the DisplayVersion value in the registry after MSIExec finishes with it.

The child is given the handle to an event that it will signal when it's

ready to do its work. For some clients, this handle is invalid. Our

ScopedHandle helper will helpfully crash the process in this case, which

is not what we want. I have tried and tried to force the handle value

given to the child to be invalid, yet I fail every time. It is my belief

that some other software on client machines is interfering with the

event handle. So, in this CL, we now handle a failure to signal the

event by releasing the ScopedHandle so that we also don't try to close

the event. This should stop the crashes. We also temporarily send a

non-fatal dump if signaling the event fails for any reason other than

ERROR_INVALID_HANDLE.

entry.title: [omnibox][ml] Redistribute shortcut boosting
entry.content:
ML scoring redistribute the traditional scores of the ML-scored

suggestions. The goal was to keep the balance between ML-scored and

non-ML-scored suggestions and avoid search regressions.



This CL makes ML scoring also redistribute the `shortcut_boosted` field

to the highest ML scored suggestions. The goal is the same; since this

field also affects ranking, we want to keep the same before/after

balance.



E.g., if we had this traditional ranking:

- shortcut 1, 1416 boosted defaultable

- shortcut 2, 1415 boosted defaultable

- search 1, 1300 defaultable

- search 2, 800

- url 3, 1414 defaultable

- url 4, 1200

- url 5, 600



Then before this CL, ML might give:

- url 3, 1414 defaultable

- search 1, 1300 defaultable

- shortcut 1, 1200 boosted defaultable

- search 2, 800

- shortcut 2, 600 boosted defaultable

- url 4, 1400

- url 5, 1416



That's bad because a) we broke search grouping, and b) search ranking

wasn't held constant. Also, in other examples, c) we might be changing

the default suggestion from a shortcut to a search.



With this CL, ML would instead give:

- url 3, 1414 boosted defaultable

- url 5, 1416 boosted

- search 1, 1300 defaultable

- search 2, 800

- url 4, 1400

- shortcut 1, 1200 defaultable

- shortcut 2, 600 defaultable



This keeps the same search v non-search rankings in this example.



This isn't a complete solution. There's still cases (both with and

without shortcut boosting) where ML will change the default suggestion

from non-search to search or vice versa or increase the # of URLs

grouped above searches. See the test for examples. That's an issue

regardless of shortcut boosting. We'll do a more robust fix as a

followup.

entry.title: snap-groups: Check `CanEnterOverview()` before SplitViewOverviewSession
entry.content:
This fixes a bug where new windows would get auto-snapped because

SplitViewOverviewSession was still alive, even though Overview wasn't,

which is why it wasn't visually noticed until now.



The cause of the bug is:

1. When the second window gets auto-snapped from

SplitViewOverviewSession, it calls `EndOverview()`.

2. `SnapGroupController::OnOverviewModeEnded()` would call `RestoreSnapStates()` to snap the windows.

3. `OnWindowSnapped()` will try to start SplitViewOverviewSession again.



During this time, we should enforce

`SnapGroupController::can_enter_overview_`, which we

can do by checking `OverviewController::Get()->CanEnterOverview()`.
